<br>
Aparently similar, but in fact very different.  In deep space you will have no atmosphere or gravity to interfere with the trajectories of the projectiles.  The projectiles will shine laser beams out the front which will impinge on targets at the far end of the catcher.  A one minute from impact, the projectile will either be on target or not.  If so, it will be accepted and if not, it will fire thrusters perpendicular to its flight path to cause it to miss the spaceship.  If it fails to do so, it will be destroyed by another projectile fired from the spaceship toward the incoming projectile.<br>
<br>
&quot;An Orion class would have higher exhaust velocity. The effective Isp could theoretically be as high as 10,000 to one million seconds. Orion would be superior as an independant spacecraft, it wouldn't rely on any new technologies, or any support infrastructure once launched, except for the occasional re-supply.&quot;<br>
<br>
The ISP estimates you give are totally unrealistic. Mallove and Matloff quote Orion project reports which predict 2000 - 6000<br>
seconds with a possible increase to 10000 - 20000.  I also strongly disagree that Orion is superior as an independent spaceship.  My spaceship will have hydroponic gardens which will be capable of feeding the entire crew indefinitely. I have<br>
not seen anything similar for Orion.  My spaceship will also provide artificial gravity of 1g which is very important because microgravity is extremely dangerous. I have seen no claim of artificial gravity for Orion.<br>
